<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-17T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-17T16:00:00-05:00" n="192" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/10338</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-17T17:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 17, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>5937. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                            <p>No. 383. Your 437 [<hi rend="italic">457</hi>], Embassy 5235,
                                September 30, midnight; and your 485, Embassy 5350, October 1 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>], 11 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d192fn2">Telegram No. 485 not printed.</note> The Government of the
                                United States has not yet been approached by the Spanish Government
                                on the subject of trading-with-enemy list for Spain. Consequently,
                                we cannot participate in any joint answer which may be sent by the
                                British and French. If, however, the British and French propose
                                making a more definite answer than that referred to your No. 437
                                    [<hi rend="italic">457</hi>], we would be glad to assist in
                                presenting a unified front to the Spanish Government by agreeing
                                that in their note they may state that the Government of the United
                                States has been advised of their views as therein expressed and
                                concurs therein. If this were done, we should, of course, desire
                                first to study the form of note which the British and French would
                                propose to deliver.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>